Multi-stage builds, and build kit.

Multi-stage builds solve a very common problem. Compiled languages, Go, Rust, Java, C plus plus, need a toolchain to build, but not to run. You really don't want your production image shipping the compiler or the whole Java development kit. The trick is to write multiple from blocks in a single docker file. The final image contains only the last stage; the earlier stages are just scratch pads.

Picture a two-stage file. The first stage, which we name builder, starts from a fat Go image that has the compiler, your source, and the dependency cache, and it builds your binary into an output folder. The second stage starts fresh from a tiny distroless image, just a few megabytes, with no shell and no package manager. Then, crucially, copy from-builder pulls in just the compiled binary. A Go service that would be one point five gigabytes with the full software development kit becomes about fifteen megabytes. Faster pulls, fewer vulnerabilities, and no toolchain sitting there to attack. The same pattern applies anywhere a build phase is distinct from a run phase; with Node, for instance, you build in stage one and copy just the output folder into a slim stage.

Build kit is the modern build backend, and it's the default on Docker twenty-three and later, and on Docker Desktop. It upgrades the engine well beyond the original sequential builder. It builds independent stages in parallel. It supports cache mounts, so a pip cache can be reused across builds without being baked into a layer. It supports build secrets, so a build can read a secret without committing it to a layer. And it supports cross-platform builds, so you can build for both amd sixty-four and arm sixty-four from one docker file, on one machine.

The command line that drives build kit is docker build-x, which is now the default builder, so most of the time docker build and docker build-x build are interchangeable. Put together, multi-stage builds plus build kit are how you get small, fast, reproducible images, which is the payoff of everything in this module.
